1 Overview and goals

After creating a pool of questionnaire items, and possibly reduce the pool employing an expert review and an item sort task, this pool is administered to a development sample. In some cases, other construct-related questionnaires are included to decide which items to retain and which to remove. Part of these methods is usually some sort of item analysis and an exploratory factor analysis. Depending on the context or goal of the questionnaire, different methods might be appropriate. This example here will cover the following:

  1. Data cleaning
  2. Descriptive analysis
  3. Item analysis
  4. Exploratory factor analysis
  5. Confirmatory factor analysis

Packages used in this example:

library(psych)

2 Description of the dataset

The dataset in this example consists of 577 rows (observations) and 105 variables. It was collected for the development of a measure of users motivation to use technology. Users of Facebook rated a set of 93 items representing six constructs on 7-point agreement scale. The answering scale was partially labeled with labels for the leftmost (âstrongly disagreeâ) and rightmost (âstrongly agreeâ) option with numbers from 1 to 7 for all options.

Additionally, demographic information and self-reported Facebook use were collected.

The variable âlfdnâ is the unique participant id, duration is the response time of the questionnaire in seconds, âv_Assentâ and âconsentâ were two options that each person willing to participate had to tick, âageâ is age in years, âgenderâ has 4 levels (female, male, prefer not to answer, another gender), âv_788â is a text field with participants own description of their gender, âv_89â is a measure of Facebook use described more in detail later on. âv_Seriousâ is a measure of self-reported carelessness in filling in the questionnaire.

Variables âv_468â up to âv_561â are questionnaire items with two bogus items âv_563â and âv_455â. The variable âv_563â was later added to the questionnaire, therefore at least 58 participants have missing values at this variable. Participants were stopped from answering the questionnaire if they did not pass these attention checks. Therefore we can remove all observations that did not see the last variable of the data set (âv_561â).

2.3 Special data cleaning procedures

2.3.1 Long String Analysis

We check only the questionnaire items of the UMI part, excluding the attention check item. Ususally, any participants with longer strings than 47 they will be removed (93/2=47). However, we will only investigate this descriptively at this point because it might be theoretically possible that only one motivation was dominant for a participant, thus they might answered 5 out of 6 items similarly.

df <- data[,c(9:104)] # make a new data frame with only the important items
df$v_563 <- NULL # remove attention check 1
df$v_455 <- NULL # remove attention check 2
df <- as.data.frame(df)

# function to investigate carelessness
seqByRow <- function(row) {
  row <- as.numeric(row)
  count <- 0
  inSequence <- FALSE
  pos <- c()
  for (i in 1:length(row)) {
    if(i > 1) {
      if(inSequence == FALSE) {
        index <- i
      }
      if(identical(as.numeric(row[i]), as.numeric(row[i-1]))) {
        pos <- c(pos, index-1)
        inSequence <- TRUE
        count <- count + 1 
      } else {
        inSequence <- FALSE
      }
    }
  }
  if(!is.null(pos)){ 
  position <- names(table(pos)[table(pos)+1 == max(table(pos)+1)])
  value <- row[as.numeric(position)]
  length <- max(table(pos)+1)
  }
  else {
    position <- 0
    value <- 0
    length <- 0
  }
  return(data.frame(position, length, value))
}

out <- data.frame()
for (id in row.names(df)) {
  out <- rbind(out, data.frame(id, seqByRow(df[id,]))[1,])
}
max(out$length)
## [1] 81
boxplot(out$length)

2.3.2 Person total correlation

Person total correlation describes how similar the answering pattern of a particular person is when compared to the mean values of all participants. Curran (2016) suggest that negative Person total correlation is evidence of carelessness. Since we have a large sample here, we will remove any observations with poor fit.

pers_tot_cor <- apply(df, 1, function(x) {
  cor(x,colMeans(df))
})

#which(pers_tot_cor < 0) # correlations below 0 are certainly strange
table(pers_tot_cor < 0) # there are 27 participants
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
##   472    24
data <- data[!(pers_tot_cor < 0),]
df <- df[!(pers_tot_cor < 0),]

Now the data frame has 472 rows. There are other measures of carelessness that might be applicable, but for this example, we will stop here and investigate the cleaned data set now.

3 Item Analysis

Item analysis is usually done on a construct level. In this data set, we have six different constructs and items which theoretically belong to only one of these constructs. Thus, it makes sense to investigate item characteristics on a construct level and not on a full-scale level. However, this is context specific, and there might be situations where a scale-level analysis is more appropriate.

According to Moosbrugger & Kelava (2008), it is advisable to investigate 1) the difficulty, 2) variance and 3) discriminatory power of items.

First, we will name the items correctly.

df <- data[,c(9:103)]
df$v_563 <- NULL # remove attention check 1
df$v_455 <- NULL # remove attention check 2
df <- as.data.frame(df)

var_names <- read.table(url("https://bruehlmann.io/projects/umi/data/var_names.txt"))
constructs <- read.table(url("https://bruehlmann.io/projects/umi/data/const_names.txt"))
names(df) <- var_names$x
constructs <- constructs$x

df <- df[ , order(names(df))] # reorder based on varname

3.2 Difficulty indices

The difficulty of an item is an important property for performance tests or other psychological tests. It describes the âeasinessâ of an item, meaning that an item with a higher difficulty was more often answered correctly by the participants. Ideally, an item has a difficulty that is not too low (too hard) but also not too high (too easy), since these items do not differentiate well between participants.

Difficulty in the context of Likert scale items means: The smaller the value, the harder (on average) it is to agree to this item.

The answers to the items need to be between 0 and k-1. K describes the number of steps on the scale. Based on Dahl (1971) in Moosbrugger & Kevala (2008), the difficulty index for scales with k > 2 levels can be calculated with this formula:

\[ P_{i}=\frac{\sum\limits_{v=1}^n{x_{vi}}}{n\cdot(k-1)}\cdot100 \]

The difficulty index of an item is thus the average of item answers for n participants on the k-steps scale. The larger this value, the âeasierâ it is on average to agree to this item.

An ideal difficulty index is about 50. But it depends on the application of the questionnaire whether a lower or higher difficulty is acceptable. For instance, if we want to have a measure that is also able to distinguish in the extremes of a feature or trait, we should include items with high and low difficulty. However, these items should also have a large discriminatory power.

diff_index <- colSums(df-1, na.rm = TRUE) / (nrow(df-1)*(max(df-1, na.rm = TRUE))) * 100

3.3 Itemvariance

The item variance is related to the item difficulty; items with low or high difficulty indices will generally have lower variance (inverted u-shape relationship). The item variance can be described as the product of the probability to solve an item and the counter-probability of not solving a particular item. The variance of responses on items should be high for items that are good at distinguishing different groups of participants (e.g.Â performance levels). Here we will remove items with a variance below 1.

remove <- c()
for(i in names(df)) {
  col <- df[,i]
  print(paste(round(var(col),2), i))
  if (var(col) < 1) {
    remove <- c(remove, i)
  }
  #print(sum((col - diff_index[i]/100*(7-1))^2)/nrow(df))
}

3.4 Discriminatory power

Discriminatory power (TrennschÃ¤rfe) indicates the correlation of the item values with the testvalues/sumscore made with all items.

âDie TrennschÃ¤rfge gibt an, wie stark die Differenzierung des jeweiligen Items mit der Differenzierung der zum Testwert zusammengefassten Ã¼brigen Items Ã¼bereinstimmt.â

With polytomous items (Likert scale), the corrected item - total correlation is equal to the discriminatory power. This is the correlation of a certain item with the sum score of all items (without this specific item). This measure is calculated as follows:

\[ r_{it(i)}=\frac{r_{it}SD(x)-SD(x_{i})}{\sqrt{SD(x)^2+SD(x_{i})^2-2r_{it}SD(x)SD(x_{i})}} \] According to Moosbrugger & Kevala (2008), these values should ideally be between .4 and .7. Items with values close to 1 are expected to measure the same thing as the complete questionnaire (or subscale). Items close to 0 do not show a sufficient correlation with the scale and are unable to differentiate between participants with high or low levels on a scale.

However, the items should have sufficient âhomogeneityâ and should not measure different constructs. Thus, it is advisable to calculate this measure on a subscale/construct level.

The corrected item-total correlation is calculated in the alpha function of the psych package. The value for this can be found in the r.cor part of the output.

alphas <- data.frame()
for(i in constructs) {
  alphas <- rbind(alphas, data.frame(i, alpha = alpha(df[,grep(i, names(df))])$total["raw_alpha"]))
}
alphas

## 3 3_INTROJECTED 0.9429020
## 4  4_IDENTIFIED 0.9303462
## 5  5_INTEGRATED 0.9762475
## 6   6_INTRINSIC 0.9502684
disc_power <- data.frame()
for(i in constructs) {
  disc_power <- rbind(disc_power, alpha(df[,grep(i, names(df))])$item.stats["r.cor"])
}
hist(disc_power[,"r.cor"])

According to Borg and Groenen (2005), the lowest acceptable discriminatory power is .30. Any items that are below this value will be removed.

row.names(disc_power)[disc_power < .3]
## [1] "6_INTRINSIC_224"
## this item will be removed
df <- df[,!(disc_power < .3)]

3.5 Intercorrelation matrix + Homogeneity

Usually, the intercorrelation matrix of the scale is reported in the paper. In this particular case, the intercorrelation matrix for 93 items (or 90) is way too large to include. However, we can still investigate these correlations on a construct level.

Additionally, Homogeneity can be useful as a measure of the mean inter-item correlation of an item (Briggs and Cheek, 1986).
We decided here to remove any items with an average inter-item correlation (Homogeneity) of less than .5.

THRESHOLD <- .5 # specify here the cut-off for the minimum inter-item correlation

stats <- data.frame()
item_stats <- list()
remove <- c()
par(mfrow = c(2,3)) # set up plot

for (i in constructs) { # calculated for each construct separately
  cor_mat <- cor(df[,grep(i, names(df))]) # get only items of a certain construct and calculate a matrix
  pairs.panels(df[,grep(i, names(df))], scale = FALSE, jiggle = TRUE) # output a correlations plot with these 
  # alternative visualization:
  #cor.plot(df[,grep(i, names(df))], numbers = TRUE, scale = TRUE)
  
  item_stats[[i]] <- colMeans(cor_mat, na.rm = TRUE) # add the homogeneity of each item to this list
  remove <- c(remove, dimnames(cor_mat)[[1]][colMeans(cor_mat, na.rm = TRUE) < THRESHOLD]) # items with a mean correlation of below .5 with others are added to the "remove" vector
  
  cor_mean <- mean(cor_mat[upper.tri(cor_mat)]) # mean inter-item correlation for each construct
  cor_min <- min(cor_mat[upper.tri(cor_mat)]) # min inter-item correlation 
  cor_max <- max(cor_mat[upper.tri(cor_mat)]) # max inter-item correlation
  diag(cor_mat) <- NA
  homogeniety <- colMeans(cor_mat, na.rm = TRUE) # mean inter-item correlation for each item
  homo_mean <- mean(homogeniety) 
  homo_min <- min(homogeniety)
  homo_max <- max(homogeniety)
  stats <- rbind(stats, data.frame(construct = i, cor_mean, cor_min, cor_max, homo_mean, homo_min, homo_max))
}

4 Exploratory factor analysis

4.1 What is exploratory factor analysis?

The two main goals of factor analysis is 1) to reduce complexity in a data set with the identification of dimensions to which the variables correspond to (dimension reduction) that can be used for further analysis and 2) to test the construct validity of a questionnaire or test. There are two classes of methods: exploratory factor analysis and confirmatory factor analysis. In situations where there is a clear apriori hypothesis or theory of how certain variables (items) correspond to factors and one would like to test these hypotheses, confirmatory factor analysis is suitable. However, in cases where there is no clear understanding about the underlying structure of a questionnaire, exploratory factor analysis might be more appropriate in the first stages of developing a questionnaire.

The exploratory factor analysis can not test any hypotheses, and thus is usually applied at a first stage of the questionnaire development and when no clear relationships are theoretically expected or the number of items is unusally large.

4.2 Steps in a exploratory factor analysis

First, a researcher has to decide which factor extraction method will be used. Then, a factor retention method should be selected and third, a method for factor rotation should be selected.

4.3 How does exploratory factor analysis work?

For a set of observed response variables, the goal is to find a set of latent factors, fewer in number than the observed variables. These factors should explain the intercorrelations of the observed variables in the sense that when the factors are partialed out from the observed variables, there should no longer remain any correlations between these. The term exploratory means that it is unknown how many factors are needed and one does one know the factorial nature of the observed variables.

4.4 When is factor analysis appropriate?

There are various recommendations about the appropriate number of participants in a sample to conduct factor analysis. In general, the more the better, but also the participant-to-variable ratio should be at least 5:1 or a sample size of at least 200 people seems appropriate.

4.5 Bartlettâs test

This test examines whether the correlation matrix is significanlty different from an identity matrix (Hauptdiagonalelemente 1, Ausserdiagonalelemente 0). If the null hypothesis can not be rejected, the process of Factor Analysis has to stop right here. This would indicate that the correlations between the variables is just accidential.

library(psych)
rmat <- cor(df, use = "complete.obs")
cortest.bartlett(rmat, nrow(df)) # there are 458 complete obs
## $chisq
## [1] 38778.11
## 
## $p.value
## [1] 0
## 
## $df
## [1] 3160

The result is highly significant - good!

4.6 Kaiser-Meyer-Olkin measure (KMO)

Examines the Anti-Image correlation matrix (negative partial correlation matrix). The partial correlation between two variables is the correlation between these variables if influence of all the other variables has been subtracted out. If two variables have a common factor, the partial correlation betwwen these variables should be approximately zero. A factor analysis is only appropriate if these partial correlations have no substantial correlation.
The KMO measure of factor adequacy is the sum of the bivariate correlations divided by the sum of the bivariate correlations and the sum of the partial correlations. This KMO measure is limited by 1. Values close to 1 indicate low partial correlations, which is a sign of common factors.

KMO(rmat)

4.6.1 Determine number of factors

There are several procedures to decided how many factors to retain. The classic (SPSS) approach is to retain factors with eigenvalues larger than 1. This basically means that the variance explained by this factor is higher than those explaned by any variable in the data. However, this criterion is very arbitrary, since factors can be by coincidence just below 1 (Kaiser criterion). One of the better approaches is the analysis of Scree Plots, in which an investigater subjectively decideds where the âkneeâ of the plot is, and keeps all the factors above this knee. A different but also very convincing approach is to use Parallel Analysis. The basic idea of Parallel Analysis is that the found number of factors is compared to a number of factors extracted from data with random correlations.

fa.parallel(df, fm = "pa")

## Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  6  and the number of components =  4

Parallel Analysis suggests 6 factors - great!

5 Confirmatory factor analysis

Confirmatory Factor Analysis (CFA) describes the measurement model part in methods for Structural Equation Modelling (SEM). The goal of CFA is data reduction; however, in contrast to EFA, the reduction is theory-guided. Researchers test hypotheses regarding the number of underlying factors of the variables and the relationships between these factors. These hypotheses are drawn from theory and need to be known to conduct the analysis. In general, CFA tests whether sufficient conformance between the empirical data and the theoretical model can be found or whether the model needs to be respecified. CFA allows to test specific model or multiple possible models and compare them with a single data set.

More details on CFA can be found here (German only): Structural Equation Models on R-Toolbox

5.1 CFA steps

  1. Specify model
  2. Decide on the estimation method
  3. Evaluate the model

5.1.1 Specify model

Decide how many factors underly the data, whether these factors have some relationship between them, and which indicators (manifest variables) load on which factor. Ideally, draft this on a paper and then create a digital visual representation of the model.

It is crucial that the model is identifiable. This means that the number of empirical variances and covariances of the manifest indicator variables need to be larger than the number of estimated parameters. In essence, the model requires a positive number of degrees of freedom.

5.1.2 Estimation method

There are several estimation methods which provide different advantages and disadvantages. Historically, maximum-likelihood is the most frequently applied since. However, this method requires interval scaled variables and multivariate normal distribution. Especially the later is almost never given, and with Likert-type scales, interval scale properties are also often disputed.

A more detailed discussion of different estimation methods can be found here. In practice, it often makes sense to use a robust estimation method.

5.1.3 Model evaluation

Several alternative model fit indicators exist. The most prominent (and most strict) measure is the \(\chi^{2}\)-Value. It should be as low as possible, and the related p-value should be not significant, \(p>.05\) (Hooper, Coughlan, & Mullen, 2008). Alternatively, Root Mean Square Error of Approximation (RMSEA) as a measure of approximate fit can be used. The RMSEA should be below \(.05\), and its associated test (PCLOSE) should be not significant. The Standardized Root Mean Square Residual (SRMR) is an alternative measure that is dependent on sample size and should ideally also be below \(.05\). Other descriptive measures (see Table below) include GFI and CFI measures which compare the model with a more or less sensible null model (e.g., all manifest variables uncorrelated).

Fit indices for CFA model evaluation.
Fit index Source
Low \(\chi^2\) value and \(p > .05\) Hooper, Coughlan, and Mullen (2008)
\(\chi^2/df < 3\) Wheaton (1977), Tabachnick and Fidell (2007)
\(RMSEA < .05\) Hu and Bentler (1999), Steiger (2007)
$SRMR 0.5 $ Byrne (2013, 1998), Diamantopoulos and Siguaw (2013)
\(95 \leq GFI \leq 1\) Tabachnick and Fidell (2007), Miles and Shevlin (2007)
\(.85 \leq AGFI \leq 1\) Tabachnick and Fidell (2007)
\(.97 \leq CFI \leq 1\) Hu and Bentler (1999)
\(.95 \leq IFI \leq 1\) Miles and Shevlin (2007)

5.2 CFA Example

The EFA example includes two models, the six and five-factor model for the User Motivation Inventory. While the results of these two EFAs are interesting to help decide which items to remove or retain, one may be interested in testing whether 6 or 5 factors better describe the data. This can be specified and tested with CFA.

For this example, we use only the 18 items included in the final version of the UMI.

library(lavaan, warn.conflicts = FALSE) # R package for SEM
## This is lavaan 0.5-23.1097
## lavaan is BETA software! Please report any bugs.
df_cfa <- df[,c("1_AMOTIV_213", "1_AMOTIV_216", "1_AMOTIV_84", "2_EXTERNAL_162",

"4_IDENTIFIED_230", "5_INTEGRATED_108", "5_INTEGRATED_129", "5_INTEGRATED_242", 
"6_INTRINSIC_222", "6_INTRINSIC_223", "6_INTRINSIC_3")]

5.2.2 Run CFA

## rename data
names(df_cfa) <- c("am1", "am2", "am3", "ex1", "ex2", "ex3", "ij1", "ij2", "ij3", 
"id1", "id2", "id3", "it1", "it2", "it3", "im1", "im2", "im3"
)
####################################
### test base model with 6 factors ####
model <- "IMO =~ im1 + im2 + im3
          INT =~ it1 + it2 + it3
          IDE =~ id1 + id2 + id3
          INJ =~ ij1 + ij2 + ij3
          EXT =~ ex1 + ex2 + ex3
          AMO =~ am1 + am2 + am3"


fit_6f <- cfa(model, df_cfa, estimator = "MLR") 
summary(fit_6f, fit.measures = TRUE, standardized = TRUE)

5.2.3 Model comparison

Letâs compare the six-factor model to the five-factor model (one factor for all identified and integrated items).

##################
model_5f  <- "IMO =~ im1 + im2 + im3
              INT =~ it1 + it2 + it3 + id1 + id2 + id3
              INJ =~ ij1 + ij2 + ij3
              EXT =~ ex1 + ex2 + ex3
              AMO =~ am1 + am2 + am3"

fit_5f <- cfa(model_5f, df_cfa, estimator = "MLR") 

aov <- anova(fit_6f,fit_5f)
aov
## Scaled Chi Square Difference Test (method = "satorra.bentler.2001")
## 
##         Df   AIC   BIC  Chisq Chisq diff Df diff Pr(>Chisq)    
## fit_6f 120 26462 26749 222.87                                  
## fit_5f 125 26648 26914 419.18     156.25       5  < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

If the \(\chi^{2}_{diff}\)-value is significant, the âlargerâ model with more freely estimated parameters fits the data better than the âsmallerâ model in which the parameters in question are fixed. So it âpays offâ to estimate the additional parameters and to prefer the âlargerâ model.

Thatâs what we observe here.

In case the \(\chi^{2}_{diff}\)-value is insignificant, both models fit equally well statistically, so the parameters in question can be eliminated from the model (fixed to zero) and the âsmallerâ model can be accepted just as well.

For more details visit these pages here and the Script on the R-Toolbox (German only).
